Interface PhoenixMultiMap<K,​V>

  • Type Parameters:

    All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<Map.Entry<K,​V>>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbsEmptyMutablePMMap, AbsFlexiMutablePMMap, AbsPhoenixMultiMap, AbsPlainMapMutablePMMap, AbsSharedKeyMutablePMMap, AbsSingleEntryMutablePMMap, EmptyFrozenPMMap, EmptyMutablePMMap, FlexiFrozenPMMap, FlexiMutablePMMap, PlainMapFrozenPMMap, PlainMapMutablePMMap, SharedKeyFrozenPMMap, SharedKeyMutablePMMap, SingleEntryFrozenPMMap, SingleEntryMutablePMMap, TreeMapPhoenixMultiMap, TreeMapSingleValuePhoenixMultiMap
    public interface PhoenixMultiMap<K,​V>
extends Iterable<Map.Entry<K,​V>>
    A PhoenixMultiMap is a mutable collection of key-to-value entries. Entries are considered to be ordered, with the entries being ordered by key. A destructive object implements all update operations by returning an object which might or might not be new - but the old value is invalidated and you are obliged to continue with the returned value ("phoenixed"). This mutation pattern is designed for uniquely referenced values (i.e. components), such as lists, whose implementation needs to be dynamically varied.
    Author:
    steve
